{"id":"1110.5550","submitter":"Haitang Yang","authors":"Peng Wang, Haitang Yang and Xiuming Zhang","title":"Quantum gravity effects on compact star cores","comments":"12 pages, 1 figure, added brief review on compact stars\n  configurations, abstract expanded, references added, typo corrected,\n  published version","journal-ref":"Physics Letters B 718 (2012), pp. 265-269","doi":"10.1016/j.physletb.2012.10.071","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Using the Tolman-Oppenheimer-Volkoff equation and the equation of state of\nzero temperature ultra-relativistic Fermi gas based on generalized uncertainty\nprinciple (GUP), the quantum gravitational effects on the cores of compact\nstars are discussed. Our results show that ${2m(r)}/ {r}$ varies with $r$.\nQuantum gravity plays an important role in the region $ r\\sim 10^3 r_0$, where\n$r_0\\sim \\beta_0 l_p $, $l_p$ is the Planck length and $\\beta_0$ is a\ndimensionless parameter accounting for quantum gravity effects. Furthermore,\nnear the center of compact stars, we find that the metric components are\n$g_{tt}\\sim r^4$ and $g_{rr}=[1-{r}^2/(6r_0^2)]^{-1}$. All these effects are\ndifferent from those obtained from classical gravity. These results can be\napplied to neutron stars or denser ones like quark stars. The observed masses\nof neutron stars ($\\leq 2M_\\odot$) indicate that $\\beta_0$ can not exceed\n$10^{37}$, not as good as the upper bound $\\beta_0<10^{34}$ from simple\nelectroweak consideration. This means that incorporating either quantum gravity\neffects or nuclear interactions, one obtains almost the same mass limits of\nneutron stars.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Oct 2011 16:00:51 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 21 Nov 2012 05:57:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-30"}
